# Charm Payments — Master Cursor Rule

You are working on Charm Payments — a merchant payment processing platform (Next.js 14 App Router on Vercel).

## IDENTITY
- Product: Charm Payments — merchant payment processing (not a bank, not a consumer wallet)
- Users: Small and mid-size business owners applying for merchant accounts
- Stack: Next.js 14 (App Router) + TypeScript + Tailwind + Supabase
- Gateway: NMI with First Data/Fiserv acquiring
- CRM: Salesforce (via Zapier webhooks)
- Brand: Primary #0c3a30 (dark green) · Accent #C9A96E (gold)
- Email: merchants@charmpayments.com
- Phone: +1 (314) 555-0198
- Copyright: © Charm Payments — A Charm Holdings LLC Company

## CURRENT ARCHITECTURE (post Phase 5 cleanup)
The app is a marketing + lead acquisition surface. There is no merchant portal and no admin portal.
All merchant management and CRM operations happen in Salesforce.

```
charmpayments.com
  ├── Marketing pages (static, 34+ routes)
  ├── /apply (public merchant application form)
  ├── /api/apply (saves to Supabase → Zapier → Salesforce)
  ├── /api/quote (rate audit form → Zapier → Salesforce)
  ├── /api/contact (contact form → lead)
  ├── /api/leads (inbound lead capture)
  ├── /api/tickets (inbound support tickets)
  └── /api/webhooks/nmi (NMI approval webhook — HMAC verified)
```

## CURSOR PROMPT RULES
- When editing code, put the **file path at the top** of the request when it helps scope the change.
- Prefer **Server Components** by default in `page.tsx`; use `'use client'` only when hooks or browser APIs are required.
- **Never** use the `.reveal` class on **static** server-rendered blocks — it requires client JS to add `.visible` and can leave content invisible.
- Deliver **complete files** or complete diffs — no placeholders, no `TODO` stubs, unless the user explicitly allows them.

## COMPLIANCE DISCLAIMER (required on every page mentioning payment processing)
"Charm Payments is a payment facilitator, not a bank. Payment processing services are provided through our licensed acquiring bank partner. Merchant funds are subject to the terms of the Merchant Agreement."

## PRODUCTS (reference naming)
- **Charm Payments** — core merchant processing, gateway, underwriting
- **Charm Cards** — digital + physical NFC business cards
- **Wallet** — Apple / Google Wallet passes where relevant

## CONTEXT (team & ops)
- Primary operator context: **Lee Robertson**, St. Louis–area operations
- Support and merchant-facing email: **merchants@charmpayments.com**
- Local positioning: **St. Louis** trusted partner

## COPY RULES (compliance-adjacent)
- 8th grade reading level max
- Never: "unhackable", "guaranteed approval", "lowest rates in the industry"
- CTAs must be descriptive: "Apply for Your Merchant Account" not "Submit"
- Rate claims must be specific and complete

## SEO
- Title: "[Page Name] — Charm Payments"
- Meta description: 150-160 chars, merchant search intent
- One H1 per page

## NAVBAR (marketing) — `src/components/marketing/Navbar.tsx`
- **`'use client'`** — dropdown hover/click state, Escape, and click-outside to close.
- **Desktop nav:** Products mega-menu · Solutions mega-menu · Gateway menu · Pricing · Contact · Apply Now (CTA)
- **No "Merchant Login" link** — merchant portal removed in Phase 5.
- Mobile: same groups as accordion sections in the slide-down panel.

## PRODUCTION BUILD — EXPECTED OUTPUT

npm run build must complete with zero errors.
All marketing pages must remain ○ static.
API routes must remain ƒ dynamic.

## OOMA INTEGRATION
- All Ooma formatting goes through `src/lib/integrations/ooma.ts`
- Env vars: `OOMA_EXTENSION`, `OOMA_ACCOUNT_ID`
- Never expose integration tokens to the client

## ZAPIER INTEGRATION (Phase 6)
- All Zapier webhook calls go through `src/lib/integrations/zapier.ts`
- Env var: `ZAPIER_SALESFORCE_WEBHOOK`
- Fire-and-forget pattern: never block primary response on Zapier failure
- Never expose the webhook URL to the client
